Overview¶

A global environmental agency has tasked me with understanding climate change. The goal is to identify changes of the Artic and Antarctic ice area thickness on a month to month basis. It could drive political action on global warming and climate change. We will be using two different types of time series models to predict this, including ARIMA and SARIMA in order to do this, which will be explained in further detail below.

ARIMA Model¶

In this section, we will use the ARIMA model, which is short for Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average, which combines three components: The Autoregressive (AR), Differencing (I), and Moving Average (MA) which help capture different patterns in time series data. The AR component models the correlation between an observation and previous (lagged) observations, denoted by 'p'. The Integrated (I) component makes the time series stationary, meaning the mean and variance do not change over time. The Moving Average (MA) component models the dependency between an observation and residual error from a moving average of lagged observations.

Based on the ACF plots, it looks like we can use the order of differencing parameter to be 3. The series may be over-differenced here, but it seems much better than the 1st and 2nd order differencing, so we will go with it.

SARIMA Model¶

Next we will use SARIMA, which is an extension of ARIMA. SARIMA can handle seasonal patterns in time series data, while ARIMA cannot. In our case, there is a seasonal pattern in the data as seen in the exploratory data analysis section. There are new hyperparameters in the model to consider, not just the p, d, and q of ARIMA. The SARIMA-specific hyperparameters include P: the seasonal autoregressive order, D: seasonal difference order, Q: seasonal moving average order, and m: the number of time steps for a single seasonal period. The notation is specified as SARIMA(p,d,q)(P,D,Q)m.

# use grid search to find optimal seasonal parameters 
import itertools
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX

# Define the seasonal frequency (s) for your data
s = 12  # Assuming monthly data with a seasonal frequency of 12

# Define the p, d, and q parameters to take any value between 0 and 2
p = d = q = range(0, 3)
pdq = list(itertools.product(p, d, q))

# Define the seasonal P, D, and Q parameters to take any value between 0 and 1
P = D = Q = range(0, 2)
seasonal_pdq = [(x[0], x[1], x[2], s) for x in itertools.product(P, D, Q)]

# Find the best SARIMA model parameters based on the lowest AIC value
best_aic = np.inf
best_pdq = None
best_seasonal_pdq = None
best_model = None

for param in pdq:
    for param_seasonal in seasonal_pdq:
        try:
            # Fit a SARIMA model with the current parameter combination
            model = SARIMAX(df['area'], order=param, seasonal_order=param_seasonal)
            results = model.fit()

            # Check if the current model has a lower AIC value than the previous best model
            if results.aic < best_aic:
                best_aic = results.aic
                best_pdq = param
                best_seasonal_pdq = param_seasonal
                best_model = results
        except:
            continue

#print(f"Best SARIMA Model: PDQ = {best_pdq}, Seasonal PDQ = {best_seasonal_pdq}, AIC = {best_aic}")

Conclusion¶

The SARIMA model had lower AIC and BIC, as well as better predictions compared to the ARIMA model. This can be attributed to the fact that the model had a seasonality component, and SARIMA is able to deal with that while ARIMA does not.
